[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":577},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F31\u002Fjavascript-core-09-threads-sync-async\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F31\u002Fjavascript-core-09-threads-sync-async\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F31\u002Fjavascript-core-09-threads-sync-async\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F31\u002Fjavascript-core-09-threads-sync-async\u002F":552,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F31\u002Fjavascript-core-09-threads-sync-async\u002F":561},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20200531\u002F3571534372\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":534,"date":535,"description":536,"extension":537,"lang":538,"meta":539,"navigation":540,"path":541,"readingMinutes":542,"seo":543,"standalone":544,"stem":545,"tags":546,"tldr":549,"updated":535,"url":550,"__hash__":551},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-core-09-threads-sync-async.md","JavaScript Core Concepts (9): Threads, Sync, and Async — Why Order Matters","1000625604",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":528},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,27,30,37,45,51,54,61,64,70,73,77,82,88,91,226,243,246,369,372,378,381,495,508,512,524],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"This is where we get into one of the really important ideas in JavaScript — the classic sync, async, and single-threaded stuff that confuses a lot of people.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"single-threaded","Single-threaded",[17,25,26],{},"Before we talk about single-threaded, let's get clear on what a thread actually is.",[17,28,29],{},"You've probably seen the word \"thread\" most often on CPU specs. As an example, here's a random screenshot I grabbed from PChome of the Intel Core i7-9700:",[17,31,32],{},[33,34],"img",{"alt":35,"src":36},"Cores \u002F Threads: 8 \u002F 8","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-05-31%2022.14.22.png",[17,38,39,40,44],{},"See where it says ",[41,42,43],"strong",{},"8 threads","? What does that 8 mean? Basically, a thread is how many things the CPU can do at the same time. Like, you can open Word, then Chrome, then Photoshop all at once — and each of those can be handed off to a different thread. The nice part is that opening Photoshop doesn't make Word lag, and opening Chrome doesn't make Photoshop lag. One thing to watch out for though: the number of cores does NOT equal the number of threads. For example, AMD's Ryzen 9 3950X has 16 cores but 32 threads.",[17,46,47],{},[33,48],{"alt":49,"src":50},"AMD Ryzen 9 3950X","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-05-31%2022.22.14.png",[17,52,53],{},"Basically a thread is a simulated core, so don't assume X cores always means X threads.",[17,55,56,57,60],{},"Now that we've got the basics of threads, let's come back to JavaScript. JavaScript is actually a single-threaded language, which means it can only do one thing at a time. This is the key point, so pay attention — ",[41,58,59],{},"it can only do one thing at a time",".",[17,62,63],{},"So JavaScript has to finish one task before it can move on to the next. To put it in everyday terms: Ming can only eat breakfast first, then call his aunt, and then wash the dishes. One thing at a time.",[17,65,66],{},[33,67],{"alt":68,"src":69},"One thing at a time","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-05-31%2022.25.41.png",[17,71,72],{},"If Ming could eat breakfast, call his aunt, and wash dishes all at the same time, that would be multi-threaded. A well-known multi-threaded language would be Java.",[12,74,76],{"id":75},"async","Async",[17,78,79],{},[33,80],{"alt":76,"src":81},"https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-05-31%2022.31.58.png",[17,83,84,85,60],{},"At this point someone might say, \"But doesn't JavaScript have async? Isn't that basically multi-threading? Isn't it doing a bunch of things at once?\" In short: ",[41,86,87],{},"threads are about the system itself, while async is about the programming language itself",[17,89,90],{},"The idea behind sync is that when code runs, it always finishes one step before moving to the next. Take this code for example:",[92,93,98],"pre",{"className":94,"code":95,"language":96,"meta":97,"style":97},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","function a() {\n  console.log('a');\n}\nfunction b() {\n  console.log('b');\n}\nfunction c() {\n  console.log('c');\n}\na();\nb();\nc();\n","js","",[99,100,101,118,137,143,153,167,172,182,196,201,210,218],"code",{"__ignoreMap":97},[102,103,106,110,114],"span",{"class":104,"line":105},"line",1,[102,107,109],{"class":108},"sWyjQ","function",[102,111,113],{"class":112},"sj_SG"," a",[102,115,117],{"class":116},"sMAXC","() {\n",[102,119,121,124,127,130,134],{"class":104,"line":120},2,[102,122,123],{"class":116},"  console.",[102,125,126],{"class":112},"log",[102,128,129],{"class":116},"(",[102,131,133],{"class":132},"sTRMh","'a'",[102,135,136],{"class":116},");\n",[102,138,140],{"class":104,"line":139},3,[102,141,142],{"class":116},"}\n",[102,144,146,148,151],{"class":104,"line":145},4,[102,147,109],{"class":108},[102,149,150],{"class":112}," b",[102,152,117],{"class":116},[102,154,156,158,160,162,165],{"class":104,"line":155},5,[102,157,123],{"class":116},[102,159,126],{"class":112},[102,161,129],{"class":116},[102,163,164],{"class":132},"'b'",[102,166,136],{"class":116},[102,168,170],{"class":104,"line":169},6,[102,171,142],{"class":116},[102,173,175,177,180],{"class":104,"line":174},7,[102,176,109],{"class":108},[102,178,179],{"class":112}," c",[102,181,117],{"class":116},[102,183,185,187,189,191,194],{"class":104,"line":184},8,[102,186,123],{"class":116},[102,188,126],{"class":112},[102,190,129],{"class":116},[102,192,193],{"class":132},"'c'",[102,195,136],{"class":116},[102,197,199],{"class":104,"line":198},9,[102,200,142],{"class":116},[102,202,204,207],{"class":104,"line":203},10,[102,205,206],{"class":112},"a",[102,208,209],{"class":116},"();\n",[102,211,213,216],{"class":104,"line":212},11,[102,214,215],{"class":112},"b",[102,217,209],{"class":116},[102,219,221,224],{"class":104,"line":220},12,[102,222,223],{"class":112},"c",[102,225,209],{"class":116},[17,227,228,229,232,233,236,237,239,240,242],{},"Here, it will always wait for ",[99,230,231],{},"a()"," to finish before running ",[99,234,235],{},"b()",". With sync, it will never jump to ",[99,238,235],{}," just because ",[99,241,231],{}," is still busy fetching data.",[17,244,245],{},"So what happens if it's async? Here's an async example:",[92,247,249],{"className":94,"code":248,"language":96,"meta":97,"style":97},"function a() {\n  console.log('a');\n}\nfunction b() {\n  setTimeout(() => {\n    console.log('b');\n  }, 1000);\n}\nfunction c() {\n  console.log('c');\n}\na();\nb();\nc();\n",[99,250,251,259,271,275,283,297,310,321,325,333,345,349,355,362],{"__ignoreMap":97},[102,252,253,255,257],{"class":104,"line":105},[102,254,109],{"class":108},[102,256,113],{"class":112},[102,258,117],{"class":116},[102,260,261,263,265,267,269],{"class":104,"line":120},[102,262,123],{"class":116},[102,264,126],{"class":112},[102,266,129],{"class":116},[102,268,133],{"class":132},[102,270,136],{"class":116},[102,272,273],{"class":104,"line":139},[102,274,142],{"class":116},[102,276,277,279,281],{"class":104,"line":145},[102,278,109],{"class":108},[102,280,150],{"class":112},[102,282,117],{"class":116},[102,284,285,288,291,294],{"class":104,"line":155},[102,286,287],{"class":112},"  setTimeout",[102,289,290],{"class":116},"(() ",[102,292,293],{"class":108},"=>",[102,295,296],{"class":116}," {\n",[102,298,299,302,304,306,308],{"class":104,"line":169},[102,300,301],{"class":116},"    console.",[102,303,126],{"class":112},[102,305,129],{"class":116},[102,307,164],{"class":132},[102,309,136],{"class":116},[102,311,312,315,319],{"class":104,"line":174},[102,313,314],{"class":116},"  }, ",[102,316,318],{"class":317},"sCcAr","1000",[102,320,136],{"class":116},[102,322,323],{"class":104,"line":184},[102,324,142],{"class":116},[102,326,327,329,331],{"class":104,"line":198},[102,328,109],{"class":108},[102,330,179],{"class":112},[102,332,117],{"class":116},[102,334,335,337,339,341,343],{"class":104,"line":203},[102,336,123],{"class":116},[102,338,126],{"class":112},[102,340,129],{"class":116},[102,342,193],{"class":132},[102,344,136],{"class":116},[102,346,347],{"class":104,"line":212},[102,348,142],{"class":116},[102,350,351,353],{"class":104,"line":220},[102,352,206],{"class":112},[102,354,209],{"class":116},[102,356,358,360],{"class":104,"line":357},13,[102,359,215],{"class":112},[102,361,209],{"class":116},[102,363,365,367],{"class":104,"line":364},14,[102,366,223],{"class":112},[102,368,209],{"class":116},[17,370,371],{},"You'll notice the result is a, then c, and finally b. That's because in an async language, if an action (like fetching data) takes time to come back, it gets pushed into something called the Event queue.",[17,373,374],{},[33,375],{"alt":376,"src":377},"Event queue","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-05-31%2022.42.24.png",[17,379,380],{},"So when JavaScript runs the code above, it finishes all of the regular code first, and only then checks whether the events in the Event queue are done. To prove the point, if we change the example to this, you'll find the result is exactly the same:",[92,382,384],{"className":94,"code":383,"language":96,"meta":97,"style":97},"function a() {\n  console.log('a');\n}\nfunction b() {\n  setTimeout(() => {\n    console.log('b');\n  }, 0);\n}\nfunction c() {\n  console.log('c');\n}\na();\nb();\nc();\n",[99,385,386,394,406,410,418,428,440,449,453,461,473,477,483,489],{"__ignoreMap":97},[102,387,388,390,392],{"class":104,"line":105},[102,389,109],{"class":108},[102,391,113],{"class":112},[102,393,117],{"class":116},[102,395,396,398,400,402,404],{"class":104,"line":120},[102,397,123],{"class":116},[102,399,126],{"class":112},[102,401,129],{"class":116},[102,403,133],{"class":132},[102,405,136],{"class":116},[102,407,408],{"class":104,"line":139},[102,409,142],{"class":116},[102,411,412,414,416],{"class":104,"line":145},[102,413,109],{"class":108},[102,415,150],{"class":112},[102,417,117],{"class":116},[102,419,420,422,424,426],{"class":104,"line":155},[102,421,287],{"class":112},[102,423,290],{"class":116},[102,425,293],{"class":108},[102,427,296],{"class":116},[102,429,430,432,434,436,438],{"class":104,"line":169},[102,431,301],{"class":116},[102,433,126],{"class":112},[102,435,129],{"class":116},[102,437,164],{"class":132},[102,439,136],{"class":116},[102,441,442,444,447],{"class":104,"line":174},[102,443,314],{"class":116},[102,445,446],{"class":317},"0",[102,448,136],{"class":116},[102,450,451],{"class":104,"line":184},[102,452,142],{"class":116},[102,454,455,457,459],{"class":104,"line":198},[102,456,109],{"class":108},[102,458,179],{"class":112},[102,460,117],{"class":116},[102,462,463,465,467,469,471],{"class":104,"line":203},[102,464,123],{"class":116},[102,466,126],{"class":112},[102,468,129],{"class":116},[102,470,193],{"class":132},[102,472,136],{"class":116},[102,474,475],{"class":104,"line":212},[102,476,142],{"class":116},[102,478,479,481],{"class":104,"line":220},[102,480,206],{"class":112},[102,482,209],{"class":116},[102,484,485,487],{"class":104,"line":357},[102,486,215],{"class":112},[102,488,209],{"class":116},[102,490,491,493],{"class":104,"line":364},[102,492,223],{"class":112},[102,494,209],{"class":116},[17,496,497,498,500,501,504,505,507],{},"The reason is that JavaScript always waits for ",[99,499,231],{}," and ",[99,502,503],{},"c()"," to finish before it goes back to check whether ",[99,506,235],{}," in the Event queue is done.",[12,509,511],{"id":510},"references","References",[513,514,515],"ul",{},[516,517,518],"li",{},[206,519,523],{"href":520,"rel":521},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.hexschool.com\u002Fcourses\u002Fjs-core.html",[522],"nofollow","Hexschool - JavaScript Core (course in Mandarin)",[525,526,527],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}",{"title":97,"searchDepth":120,"depth":120,"links":529},[530,531,532,533],{"id":14,"depth":120,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":120,"text":23},{"id":75,"depth":120,"text":76},{"id":510,"depth":120,"text":511},"JavaScript","2020-05-31 22:09:11","This is where we get into one of the most important ideas in JavaScript — the whole sync vs async, single-threaded thing that trips so many people up. We'll start with what a thread even is, why JavaScript can only do one thing at a time, and how the Event queue lets it handle async work anyway.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002Fjavascript-core-09-threads-sync-async","3",{"title":6,"description":536},false,"en\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjavascript-core-09-threads-sync-async",[534,547,548],"JavaScript Core","Execution Context and Scope",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F31\u002Fjavascript-core-09-threads-sync-async\u002F","iY-62oIbxiIonwT57ciku7f1w016TeT_Ksj__S_Qn48",{"newer":553,"older":557},{"url":554,"title":555,"date":556},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2020\u002F06\u002F01\u002Fpixijs-v5-tutorial-17-text-hp\u002F","PixiJS V5 Tutorial (17) - Adding Text to Your HP Bar","2020-06-01 08:38:23",{"url":558,"title":559,"date":560},"\u002Fen\u002Fvue\u002F2020\u002F05\u002F30\u002Fdynamic-page-title-in-vue\u002F","How to Set a Dynamic Page Title in Vue","2020-05-30 21:53:33",[562,567,572],{"url":563,"title":564,"date":565,"readingMinutes":566},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2026\u002F03\u002F10\u002Fweb-crypto-api-encryption-guide\u002F","No crypto Package, No Node.js — The Web Crypto API Does It All in the Browser","2026-03-10 09:45:08","9",{"url":568,"title":569,"date":570,"readingMinutes":571},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F08\u002Fjquery-why-it-declined\u002F","jQuery Was Once King — So Why Did It Fall Off?","2025-12-08 21:35:24","7",{"url":573,"title":574,"date":575,"readingMinutes":576},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F05\u002Fjavascript-generator-functions\u002F","What Are JavaScript Generator Functions (function*)? The Function You Can Pause and Resume","2025-12-05 13:40:31","5",1784013060891]